1.3. Personal Access Token

The final bit of admin you will need to do to complete your integration of Posit Cloud and GitHub is to create a personal access token (PAT). This is used in place of a password to securely link third party applications (like Posit Cloud) to GitHub. You will need these to push your updates to your repository after you have finished editing your files.

A PAT can be generated by clicking on your profile picture in the top right of the GitHub homepage and selecting settings, and then going to ‘Developer settings’ at the bottom of the toolbar on the left.

Press the settings button in the drop down section of your profile

Go to the Developer settings tab in the settings page

Go on the ‘Personal access tokens’ tab and press the generate new tokens button on the right hand side of the page.

Click ‘Personal access tokens’ and ’Generate new token

In the note box write ‘My First PAT’, set the expiration to 90 days and click the ‘repo’ box, before hitting the green ‘Generate token’ button at the bottom of the page.

Fill in the information from above for your PAT

Hit the green button to finish

You will be given a string of letters and numbers (it should start with ‘ghp_’) and save it somewhere safe (not in your emails, best to save it in your onedrive folder somewhere).

Copy your new PAT somewhere safe!

Use the Git tab in the topright corner to commit your changes

Insertions are highlighted in green and deletions are in red. As we have only inserted some new code, we will just see our new lines highlighted in green. 2. Regular Expressions

In data science sometimes we might want to search through our data to find certain information. To do so we can use a powerful and flexible tool called a regular expression. Regular expressions not only allow you to look for specific characters, words or phrases, but can also look for complex text patterns.

Before we get going, remember that we have provided you with a regular expression cheatsheet in the ‘Useful Resources’ section of the BIO319 QM+ homepage!

2.1. An Introduction

Let us consider the following vector containing a quote from Ministry of Utmost Happiness by Arundhati Roy in the from of a character vector:

sentence <- c('By','the','time','they', 'got', 'back,', 'the', 'lights', 'were', 'all', 'out', 'and', 'everybody', 'was', 'asleep.', 'Everybody,', 'that', 'is,', 'except', 'for', 'Guih', 'Kyom', 'the', 'dung', 'beetle.', 'He', 'was', 'wide', 'awake', 'and', 'on', 'duty,', 'lying', 'on', 'his', 'back', 'with', 'his', 'legs', 'in', 'the', 'air', 'to', 'save', 'the', 'world', 'in', 'case', 'the', 'heavens', 'fell.')

If we decided we wanted to find out where the word 'the' is in this vector, we could use a function from a family of regular expression functions. Lets start with the grep() function:

grep_out <- grep(pattern = 'the', x = sentence)
grep_out
## [1]  2  4  7 23 41 45 49

First, look at the syntax of the function (the arrangement of words in our first line of code). We have defined two function arguments; pattern and 'x'. The first is the pattern that we want to look for in our text, the second is the character vector to search through (our sentence object we created above).

grep() has returned us a numeric vector. If we look carefully at these numbers, we can see that they correspond to the position of every the in our sentence vector.

We can check this using the grep_out to subscript our sentence using square brackets. This will return all the words at the positions grep() gave us.

sentence[grep_out]
## [1] "the"  "they" "the"  "the"  "the"  "the"  "the"

Note that grep() has also returned the position of 'they', as it contains 'the'. If we wanted to avoid this, you can tell grep() that you want the match to start before the ‘t’ using the ^ symbol, and end after the ‘e’ using the $ symbol by changing the pattern argument to pattern = '^the$' (these special characters are called anchors).

Start a new script called ‘RegularExpressions.R’, create the relevant variables using the code above and try using ^ and $ for yourself!

Try searching for other letters, words or word fragments using the grep() function.

You can copy the code in this worksheet by pressing the copy button in the corner.

Remember that you should be annotating your code AND committing new work to GitHub with adequate comments.

2.2. Regular Expression Tools

Regular expressions can search much more flexibly than just looking for specific words. For example, we can search for the elements that contain a capital letter using the pattern '[A-Z]'.

grep_out <- grep(pattern = '[A-Z]', x = sentence)
grep_out
## [1]  1 16 21 22 26

Alternatively we can look for lowercase letters using '[a-z]' or any letters regardless of case using '[A-z]'. Similarly we can search for numbers using '[0-9]'.

We can also use the special character '.' to specify that any character can match the search pattern. This may seem counter intuitive at first, why search for a character that will match to any other character? The power of the '.' comes into play when used with other characters. For example, if we search for 'a.e' we are looking for matches where there is an 'a' and an 'e' separated by any character.

grep_out <- grep(pattern = 'a.e', x = sentence)
sentence[grep_out]
## [1] "awake"   "save"    "case"    "heavens"

We can see in the above example that grep has found four elements of our vector that contain an 'a' and an 'e' separated by any character - awake, save, case and heavens.

Try searching through the quote yourself using some of the flexible regular expression patterns outlined above.

2.3. Quantifiers

A final important concept in regular expressions we are going to address today is the use of quantifiers. These allow the user to specify how many of a character (or set of characters) grep() is matching to. The three main symbols are ‘?’, ‘*’ and ‘+’.

‘?’ denotes 0 or 1 instances.

‘*’ denotes 0 or more instances.

‘+’ denotes 1 or more instances.

To show the difference between the three, consider the outputs of the following three lines of code:

sentence[grep(pattern = 'e.?e', x = sentence)]
## [1] "were"      "everybody" "asleep."   "beetle."
sentence[grep(pattern = 'e.*e', x = sentence)]
## [1] "were"      "everybody" "asleep."   "except"    "beetle."   "heavens"
sentence[grep(pattern = 'e.+e', x = sentence)]
## [1] "were"      "everybody" "except"    "beetle."   "heavens"

What is the difference between each line of code in the above example? How does this change what they are looking for? (Remember the full stop will match any character)

2.4. The gsub() Function

In addition to the 'grep()' function there are a whole host of other regular expression functions in R. For the purposes of today’s session, we would like to show you one more. The 'gsub()' function can be used to search for text in the same way as the 'grep()' function, but instead of finding the instances of our search term, it instead substitutes the matched text with text of our choosing.

Again using the Arundhati Roy quote, we can show what this actually means!

gsub_out <- gsub(pattern = 'a.e', x = sentence, replacement = '!!!')
gsub_out
##  [1] "By"         "the"        "time"       "they"       "got"       
##  [6] "back,"      "the"        "lights"     "were"       "all"       
## [11] "out"        "and"        "everybody"  "was"        "asleep."   
## [16] "Everybody," "that"       "is,"        "except"     "for"       
## [21] "Guih"       "Kyom"       "the"        "dung"       "beetle."   
## [26] "He"         "was"        "wide"       "aw!!!"      "and"       
## [31] "on"         "duty,"      "lying"      "on"         "his"       
## [36] "back"       "with"       "his"        "legs"       "in"        
## [41] "the"        "air"        "to"         "s!!!"       "the"       
## [46] "world"      "in"         "c!!!"       "the"        "he!!!ns"   
## [51] "fell."

We can see that where gsub() has found matches to our pattern ('a.e'), it has replaced them with ‘!!!’. This is an incredibly useful tool for fixing errors in datasets, and is one we will use in the challenge below.

Try writing your own line of code to replace all the letter ’t’s with question marks.

2.5. The Challenge

Let’s use all the regular expression knowledge that you have picked up today to solve the following challenges in a new script called ‘RegularExpressionChallenge.R’.

Remember, as you write this script, you should be annotating it AND committing frequently to keep track of changes you make.

1. Load in the ‘dung_beetles.csv’ into R

2. Have a look at the structure of the dataset. What sort of dataset do you think this is?

3. Make a new object that is a vector of all the species names so we can play around with it. The colnames() function may come in useful here… so look it up in the R documentation or search online!

4.Use your new found grep() prowess to find the names of all the species that have a genus name that starts with the letter ‘C’.

4. Find all the species where the specific epithet (the second word) starts with the letter ‘r’.

5. There is a typo in the species names! Replace all the ‘Copis’ genus names with the correct ‘Copris’ spelling.

6. Another genus name has been misspelled - ‘Microcopis’ should be ‘Microcopris’. Fix this too.

7. Make sure you have committed your last answers to Git. Now push all the commits you have made to your Git repository.

8. Now create a new gsub() command that replaces the one you used in question 5 and 6, so that it is flexible enough to fix both genus names in one go! (Once you push these changes to GitHub again, you should be able to see the changes you are making over time in the repository history!)

9. Replace the column names in your data set with your corrected ones.

2.6. Optional Super Challenge!

10. Find all the species where the genus starts with an ‘O’ and the specific epithet ends in an ‘s’.

11. Subset the dataframe using regular expressions so that it only contains data from months ending in a ‘y’ and genera starting with an ‘O’.
